    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-12-26T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-12-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="569"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d569">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.03/12–2648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-12-26T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 26, 1948—1 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:35 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2622. Tung Kuan-hsien, former North China CNRRA<note n="71" xml:id="d569fn71"
                        >Chinese National Relief and Rehabilitation Administration.</note> head,
                    elected new President Legislative Yuan December 24. Liu Chien-chun, former Youth
                    Corps officer, also previously connected with Tai Li,<note n="72"
                        xml:id="d569fn72">Former Deputy Director of the Bureau of Investigations and
                        Statistics (Chinese secret police organization).</note> elected Vice
                    President.</p>
                <p>Tung’s election a direct rebuff to Generalissimo, as he was supported by
                    coalition consisting of youth corps, Wu Tieh-cheng group, Li Tsung-jen group and
                    independents against Li Pei-chi, who was hand-picked by Generalissimo, nominated
                    by Central Political Council, and supported only by CC group. CC clique suffered
                    another blow in vice presidential election when their candidate Cheng
                        Tien-fang<note n="73" xml:id="d569fn73">Member of the Chinese Legislative
                        Yuan.</note> was defeated by same coalition.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
